<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="2754" pageId="9" pageNumber="2753" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[160,1155,1632,1727]" box="[160,276,1632,1658]" pageId="9" pageNumber="2753">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,276,1632,1658]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="2753">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[160,1155,1632,1727]" lastBlockId="10.[160,1156,142,236]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="2754" pageId="9" pageNumber="2753">
This new species is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Watanabe)" baseAuthorityName="Watanabe" baseAuthorityYear="1934" box="[559,864,1669,1693]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Bassus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="2753" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albifasciatus">
<emphasis box="[559,723,1669,1693]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="2753">B. albifasciatus</emphasis>
(Watanabe)
</taxonomicName>
, but differs in having the notauli moderately crenulate (rather narrowly crenulate in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Watanabe" baseAuthorityYear="1934" box="[910,1085,1703,1727]" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Bassus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="2753" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albifasciatus">
<emphasis box="[910,1085,1703,1727]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="2753">B. albifasciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); the mesopleuron below the precoxal sulcus with dense and rather coarse punctures (with sparse fine punctures); and the precoxal sulcus shallow and shorter (distinct and 0.8 times as long as mesopleuron).
</paragraph>
